@joewitt 

H2O has an **open source library** called **H2O-3**. Users can build and execute **MOJO pipelines**. The License Key is not required. All they need is the saved MOJO pipeline file, then they can execute it to do scoring. Would it be fine if I contributed a NiFi processor that uses this open source library? Again no license key is required. Once the user has the H2O-3 MOJO pipeline file set as a property to the NiFi processor, then can execute the processor freely.

Also the **H2O-3 open source** library has support for building and executing the **MOJO pipeline** in Python and R. Would it be fine if I contributed a MiNiFi CPP Python processor that uses this open source library?

@jfrazee I meant the `${filename}` would contain the whole object name, including the pseudo directory name too. So no path / filename separation.
In this way, the Azure Blob processors would work the same way as the S3 and GCS processors: the List processor fills in `${filename}` on the outgoing FlowFile, the others (Fetch, Put, Delete) use `${filename}` as default value.

If someone would like to handle / configure the directory and the filename separately, then the new AzureDataLakeStorage processors would be better choice. I would keep the single "Blob" property for the Blob processors.
